        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-20T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-20T01:00:00-05:00" n="263" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d263">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5–2045: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-20T13:00:00+07:00">May 20, 1945—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 20—7:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>811. If the resolutions mentioned in Embassy’s, 806, May 19, are effectively
                    implemented, thereby divorcing the army and student bosses [?] from Kuomintang
                    domination and providing for popular self-government, a most important step will
                    of course have been taken toward the achievement of democracy in China.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
